The paper presents a tool for assisting analysts during requirements elicitation process using a combination of generative and discriminative models. This involves interactive visual analytics with a GUI that allows analysts to explore ongoing conversations or specification documents. The paper's focus on interactive visual analytics and natural language processing suggests that it is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Additionally, the use of machine learning models such as SVMs and WFSTs suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper's focus on requirements elicitation and software engineering suggests that it could also belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The use of information extraction algorithms suggests that it could also belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. Finally, the use of natural language processing techniques suggests that it could also belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category.
